Let $P$ be the point on the unit circle that is $60^\circ$ counterclockwise from $(1,0)$, and let $D$ be the foot of the altitude from $P$ to the $x$-axis, as shown below.

[asy]

pair A,C,P,O,D;

draw((0,-1.2)--(0,1.2),p=black+1.2bp,Arrows(0.15cm));

draw((-1.2,0)--(1.2,0),p=black+1.2bp,Arrows(0.15cm));

A = (1,0);

O= (0,0);

label("$x$",(1.2,0),SE);

label("$y$",(0,1.2),NE);

P = rotate(60)*A;

D = foot(P,A,-A);

draw(O--P--D);

draw(rightanglemark(O,D,P,2));

draw(Circle(O,1));

label("$O$",O,SE);

label("$P$",P,NE);

//label("$A$",A,SE);

label("$D$",D,S);

[/asy]

Triangle $POD$ is a 30-60-90 triangle, so $DO = \frac{1}{2}$ and $DP = \frac{\sqrt{3}}{2}$.  Therefore, the coordinates of $P$ are $\left(\frac{1}{2}, \frac{\sqrt{3}}{2}\right)$, so $\cos 60^\circ = \boxed{\frac{1}{2}}$.ניוזל

Since $HO$ and $HN$ are tangent to the circle at $O$ and $N$, respectively, we have $\angle HON = 90^\circ$.  Since $J$ is the center of the circle, we have $JO = JN$.  Therefore, $\triangle JNO$ is isosceles, so $\angle J = \angle H = \frac{1}{2}(180^\circ - 90^\circ) = \boxed{45^\circ}$.  Therefore, the sum of the measures of $\angle J$ and $\angle H$ is $45^\circ + 45^\circ = \boxed{90^\circ}$.  [asy]
size(150);
import graph;
pair J = (0,0), H = (6,0), O, N;
path circ = Circle(J,3);
pair M = midpoint(J--H);
path secCirc = Circle(M,3);
pair[] tangentPoints = intersectionpoints(circ,secCirc);
O = tangentPoints[0]; N = tangentPoints[1];
draw(J--N--H--O--cycle);
draw(circ);
label("$H$",H,E);
label("$J$",J,W);
label("$N$",N,S);
label("$O$",O,NE);
label("$45^\circ$",O+(0.5,0.5),NE);
label("$45^\circ$",O+(0.5,-0.5),SE);
[/asy]�始化

