Since $\triangle PQR$ is isosceles, we know that $\angle P = \angle R$.  Since the sum of the angles in a triangle is $180^\circ$, we have \begin{align*}
\angle P + \angle R + \angle Q &= 180^\circ \\
2\angle P + 40^\circ &= 180^\circ \\
2\angle P &= 140^\circ \\
\angle P &= \angle R = 70^\circ.
\end{align*}Since $\angle P$ and $\angle S$ are supplementary, we have \begin{align*}
\angle P + \angle S &= 180^\circ \\
70^\circ + x^\circ &= 180^\circ \\
x^\circ &= \boxed{110}.
\end{align*} [asy]
