Since $ABCD$ is a parallelogram, $\overline{AB} \parallel \overline{DC}$ and $\overline{AD} \parallel \overline{BC}$.  Since $\overline{AB} \parallel \overline{DC}$, the slope of $\overline{AB}$ is the same as the slope of $\overline{DC}$.  The slope of $\overline{AB}$ is $\frac{1-1}{2-0}=0$, so the slope of $\overline{DC}$ is also 0.  Since $\overline{AD} \parallel \overline{BC}$, the slope of $\overline{AD}$ is the same as the slope of $\overline{BC}$.  The slope of $\overline{BC}$ is $\frac{0-1}{4-2}=-\frac{1}{2}$, so the slope of $\overline{AD}$ is also $-\frac{1}{2}$.  Since the slope of $\overline{AD}$ is $-\frac{1}{2}$, the equation of $\overline{AD}$ is $y-1=-\frac{1}{2}x$.  Since the coordinates of $D$ must satisfy this equation, the sum of the coordinates of $D$ is $x+y=1-\frac{1}{2}x=\frac{1}{2}(2-x)$.  Since $C$ is the midpoint of $\overline{AD}$, the sum of the coordinates of $D$ is $2\cdot\frac{1}{2}(2-x)=2-x$.  Since $C$ has coordinates $(4,0)$, $2-x=4-0=\boxed{4}$.  [asy]
unitsize(0.5 cm);

pair A, B, C, D;

A = (0,1);
B = (2,1);
C = (4,0);
D = (6,-1);

draw(A--B--C--cycle);
draw(A--D);

label("$A$", A, NW);
label("$B$", B, SE);
label("$C$", C, S);
label("$D$", D, SW);
[/asy]�始化

