Let $f(x) = \sin 6 \pi x - x.$  Then
\[f'(x) = 6 \pi \cos 6 \pi x - 1.\]If $x \ge 0,$ then $6 \pi x \ge 0,$ so $\cos 6 \pi x \le 1.$  Hence, $f'(x) \le 5 \pi < 0,$ so $f(x)$ is strictly decreasing on $[0,\infty).$

If $x \le 0,$ then $6 \pi x \le 0,$ so $\cos 6 \pi x \ge -1.$  Hence, $f'(x) \ge -5 \pi < 0,$ so $f(x)$ is strictly decreasing on $(-\infty,0].$

Furthermore, $f(0) = 0,$ so $f(x) < 0$ for $x < 0$ and $f(x) > 0$ for $x > 0.$  Therefore, the graph of $y = f(x)$ looks like this:

[asy]
unitsize(1 cm);

real func (real x) {
  return(sin(6*pi*x) - x);
}

draw(graph(func,-1,1),red);
draw((-1,0)--(1,0),Arrow(6));
draw((0,-1)--(0,1),Arrow(6));
label("$y = f(x)$", (1.2,1.2), red);
label("$x$", (1.2,0), red);
label("$y$", (0,1.2), red);
label("$x$", (0,-1), red);

draw((-1,-1)--(1,1),dashed);
[/asy]

Since $f(x)$ is continuous and strictly decreasing, it has exactly one real root.  Furthermore, the root is positive, so the number of real solutions to $\sin 6 \pi x = x$ is $\boxed{1}.$

