Let $\mathbf{v} = \begin{pmatrix} a \\ b \end{pmatrix}$ be a vector in the direction of $\ell.$  Then
\[\begin{pmatrix} \frac{1}{50} & \frac{7}{50} \\ \frac{7}{50} & \frac{49}{50} \end{pmatrix} \begin{pmatrix} a \\ b \end{pmatrix} = \begin{pmatrix} \frac{a + 7b}{50} \\ \frac{7a + 49b}{50} \end{pmatrix} = \begin{pmatrix} a \\ b \end{pmatrix}.\]This gives us the equations
\begin{align*}
\frac{a + 7b}{50} &= a, \\
\frac{7a + 49b}{50} &= b.
\end{align*}From the first equation, $a + 7b = 50a,$ so $49a = 7b.$  From the second equation, $7a + 49b = 50b,$ so $7a = 11b.$  Hence, $49a = 7b = 77a,$ so $a = 0$ and $b = 0.$  This is not possible, so we must have $a = 7$ and $b = 1.$  Thus, the direction vector of $\ell$ is $\boxed{\begin{pmatrix} 7 \\ 1 \end{pmatrix}}.$

Note: The matrix is symmetric, so the line $\ell$ is the line of reflection.  The projection matrix is given by
\[\mathbf{P} = \frac{\mathbf{v} \mathbf{v}^T}{\mathbf{v}^T \mathbf{v}} = \frac{1}{7^2 + 1^2} \begin{pmatrix} 7 \\ 1 \end{pmatrix} \begin{pmatrix} 7 & 1 \end{pmatrix} = \frac{1}{50} \begin{pmatrix} 49 & 7 \\ 7 & 1 \end{pmatrix} = \begin{pmatrix} \frac{1}{50} & \frac{7}{50} \\ \frac{7}{50} & \frac{49}{50} \end{pmatrix}.\]This confirms that the direction vector of $\ell$ is $\begin{pmatrix} 7 \\ 1 \end{pmatrix}.$

