The first line passes through the point $\begin{pmatrix} 7 \\ -3 \\ 1 \end{pmatrix}$ and is parallel to the vector $\begin{pmatrix} -2 \\ 5 \\ 1 \end{pmatrix}.$  The second line passes through the point $\begin{pmatrix} 8 \\ -1 \\ -1 \end{pmatrix}$ and is parallel to the vector $\begin{pmatrix} 1 \\ -4 \\ 0 \end{pmatrix}.$  The direction vector of the first line is $-2$ times the direction vector of the second line, so the lines intersect at a point.

We can find this point of intersection by setting the two equations equal to each other:
\[\begin{pmatrix} 7 \\ -3 \\ 1 \end{pmatrix} + t \begin{pmatrix} -2 \\ 5 \\ 1 \end{pmatrix} = \begin{pmatrix} 8 \\ -1 \\ -1 \end{pmatrix} + u \begin{pmatrix} 1 \\ -4 \\ 0 \end{pmatrix}.\]This gives us the system of equations
\begin{align*}
7 - 2t &= 8 + u, \\
-3 + 5t &= -1 - 4u, \\
1 + t &= -1.
\end{align*}Solving, we find $t = -2$ and $u = 3.$  Substituting into the first equation, we find that the point of intersection is $\boxed{\begin{pmatrix} 3 \\ -7 \\ -1 \end{pmatrix}}.$

