The shortest distance from a point to a line is along the perpendicular from the point to the line.  The slope of the line $y = 2x - 2$ is 2, so the slope of the perpendicular line is $-\frac{1}{2}$.  The equation of the perpendicular line passing through $(6,0)$ is $y = -\frac{1}{2} (x - 6) = -\frac{1}{2} x + 3$.  The point of intersection of the two lines is the solution to the system of equations
\begin{align*}
y &= 2x - 2, \\
y &= -\frac{1}{2} x + 3.
\end{align*}Setting the two expressions for $y$ equal, we find $2x - 2 = -\frac{1}{2} x + 3$, so $x = 2$.  Substituting this value of $x$ into either equation, we find $y = 2$.  Thus, the point of intersection is $(2,2)$.

